## Summary

Added a **"Launch at login"** toggle to Bringr Preferences, backed by `SMAppService.mainApp`.

**What I built:**
- `Bringr/LaunchAtLogin.swift` â€” `LaunchAtLoginManager`, an `ObservableObject` mirroring `PermissionsManager`'s injectable-system-call pattern. `setEnabled(_:)` registers/unregisters then republishes the *actual* system status (a failed call can't make the toggle lie); `refresh()` re-reads to catch changes made in System Settings.
- `Bringr/PreferencesView.swift` â€” new "Startup" section with the toggle.
- `AppDelegate` owns the manager; `BringrApp` injects it into the Preferences window.
- `BringrTests/LaunchAtLoginTests.swift` â€” 7 tests over the manager logic.

**Design call:** the bead suggested adding the LaunchAtLogin-Modern SPM package via Xcode's GUI. I wrapped `SMAppService` directly instead â€” an agent can't drive Xcode's package UI, it would be the project's only SPM dependency (making the build fail offline), and the package is just a thin `SMAppService` wrapper. Behavior and the acceptance criteria (which name SMAppService) are identical. Left `AboutView` unchanged since no third-party package is bundled to credit.

**Quality gates:** build SUCCEEDED Â· `swiftlint lint --strict` 0 violations Â· 184 tests pass (+7 new, confirmed executing via `-only-testing`). App is running (PID 97583).

**Caveat:** I verified the logic via unit tests and that the app builds and launches without crashing. The actual toggle-click â†’ login-item registration and persistence-across-reboot can't be exercised in this automated environment â€” that needs a manual click and a reboot, and on this ad-hoc-signed dev build `register()` may throw (handled gracefully); it works on a properly signed build.

One thing worth flagging: a **concurrent iteration** added `WindowActivationShim.m` and modified `LiveWindowSystem.swift` in this same repo mid-task â€” those aren't my changes. The collision it caused in `project.pbxproj` was auto-resolved (the shim got renumbered), and my build is green against the combined state.

